I had a lucky escape as a lad when I had to strip down my 12 month old Honda engine........MAN were those baskits tight ! - I ripped the cross heads out of over half the side cover screws even using the impact driver and ripped the heads  clean off others, luckily for me I was an apprentice mechanic back then and had access to a compound we used regularly called copperslip, and ever since that day  I NEVER again had that struggle getting the damned japanesium bolts and screws out.', 'They really should make anything not a philips head just straight up illegal', "I've been putting off replacing yet another part to get my bike which hasn't been working for over a year, running again. ["Thank you, everyone. Thank you for following along with me and also for being patient.

With the physical car being done almost two months ago, this video should've been out much, much sooner than this. 

Part of the reason it took so long to make was honestly because I was so overwhelmed from worrying that the video wouldn't be perfect. With the intention that this is indeed going to be the last video, no more ever on the Fiero, I wanted to perfectly wrap this in a bow, but I was so afraid that whatever I did wouldn't be the perfect way to end it.

Eventually, I found a story I was happy with, and made the video into something I'm proud of.

Sorry about all the noise!", 'Just a note. Never apply antisieze to the hub / rotor mating surface. Could cause the rotor to not sit true', 'This is amazing! I love this channel!', 'My dude has a whole mr2 a sonata and a Cruze in his driveway 😂', 'I thought the composite caliper pistons were cool, then i had an immediate vietnam flashback the second you said the word "phenolic"

If you don't know, phenolics are a type of resin/plastic. They can be used in a number of things. I used to work at a cabinetry/specialties shop, and some of our biggest selling specialties were bathroom stalls and counter tops, and every now and then we'd get an order for those products made out of phenolic. And boy let me tell you, that stuff is *dense*. Like, one 4x4 foot counter top, 1.5 inches thick would weigh upwards of 100lb. Gotta love carrying that shit up the stairs to the third floor of a building under construction😂😂', 'For fucks sakes mate, heat up the rotor in an oven, say 70 celsius or so, and blast the bearing race with lighter refill canister, butane and such are quite potent cooling agents when in absence of liquid nitrogen... That would have allowed you to drop that bearing race in the bearing seat, all the way in, absolutely no force required, and no chance of messing up the bearing or the bearing seat... It would result in a 100 degrees difference between the parts, which would likely be enough to induce a clearance, as the bearings are rarely a strong interference fit, most often they are light or rarely medium interference fit... The same works for taking them out... Heat up the whole part, blast the inner race with lighter gas, and it will likely fall out on its own if you are doing that upside down... The differential temperatures will cause a gap between the parts, and often, there is no need for more than a 100 degrees difference for the parts to separate on their own, and to prevent the heated part from cooling, or the desired cold part from soaking up the heat and thus remaining the same diameter... Save your effort, save the parts from damage, and avoid the potential for either injury or smashing something that you shouldnt with a hammer... A press is just as bad as the hammer, but it has a few benefits, yet if the parts can be differentially heated/cooled, its the best approach, and the safest one by a whole ballpark of a margin... I am a certified automechatronics tech, and a machinist/millwright, so i am quite familiar with bearings and the whole shebang of dealing with shit that is supposed to be somewhere or to be extracted from somewhere where it wants to remain... A car bearing aint no precision spindle bearing, but its a ``precision`` component nonetheless and should be treated with gentleness and every other method before resorting to force of any kind...

Also, keep in mind that that wheel nut should be moderately tight... The bearings may be tapered and thus become ever harder to turn, to the point where you either brinell the bearings or seize them and thus damage them... The similarity of this spindle and a high precision machine spindle still remains... That spindle stub is elastic, and as you tighten the nut, the spindle elongates elastically somewhat, that can be measured with an indicator... That is one thing to take into consideration... Another is the loads, be it side loads, lateral loads or whatever sort of insane vector of load forces a car produces while driving... Those forces are attempting to rip your wheel off constantly, the spindle`s structural integrity prevents that shit from happening, but as with the nut, those forces elongate the spindle a bit and let it contract as the load vector shifts... The bearings should actually be preloaded somewhat, akin to machine spindle, as to prevent the bearings from ever developing a clearance and a gap of any sort between the races and the rolling elements... That is what obliterates the bearings... A properly preloaded bearing will not under any normal circumstance develop a momentary loss of full contact between the races and the rolling elements, thus greatly increasing its lifetime and performance... I cant really tell you what force to use... That should either be in the manual of the vehicle, or you can calculate it relatively simply... Look up tapered bearing preload and such... You can look up machinist related content in that topic and apply the formula and explanation for the precision spindles for this... A bearing should be able to turn by hand when the wheel hub is tightly on, but there should be some resistance to turning, it should not freewheel for a minute, it should spin one turn at the most if all is well set up... A lack of proper preload can obliterate the bearings with ease, either through increased wear, brinelling of the races, chipping of the elements surfaces and so on... 

I know that im 4 years too late for this party, but i just found the channel yesterday... Sorry if the comment may appear hostile, as its not meant to be, its a heartfelt gentle suggestion, made for the sakes of precision parts that can serve you well or get fucked in a rush and add up quickly in cost and frustration if you keep on installing them improperly... Also, dont lubricate anything with brake fluid... Use atf or whatever else, but not the bloody brake fluid... That shit will turn acidic in a hurry when exposed to air, and well, no need to explain why acidic lubricant is bad... Use forklift grease in a spray can, use atf, use gearbox oil, bearing grease, earwax, whatever just not the brake fluid... That shit should never see anything other than the dark insides of either its storage pack or the inside of the brake system... Its an amazing compound, but its literally devils tears in any situation other than its packaging or the brake sys... 

All the best, and for the love of God, dont spend 1k$ on fucking wood... Buy some good bearings, or whatever the fuck else, just not ``engineered wood``... I learned it’s best to get ChrisFix to ceramic coat your car.', "Also, please follow manufacturer guidelines on keeping the vehicle out of the elements during the cure time, which can be anywhere from 24 hours to 7 days depending on the specific coating. If you don't do so, the coating can become contaminated with minerals (essentiallythe same as water spots) and/or become uneven very easily. And in the worst case scenario, various combinations of wind, water, heat/cold, etc. can actually cause the ceramic to not adhere properly to the surface, requiring another buff  and polish step to remove the remaining ceramic and then a complete reapplication of the ceramic. 

Considering how expensive many coatings can be even for a 30mL bottle, and how time-consuming the process is, keeping the vehicle in a garage or other covered space for as long as the manufacturer recommends is the easiest way to ensure you get ideal results, and avoid wasting time and money.", 'This man only Ceramic Coated that one panel!']

The advantage of getting clear coat and hardener separated is that it can stay at the shelf for longer time. The guys who made the paint for the car can do the clear coat with the hardener already mixed up which might be cheaper but it will also mean that it will expire in like two weeks.
Same applies to the color paint. Hardener is not needed but it will need more time to dry.

Another point about electric polisher: if you don't have the experience and you are not planning with getting a wrap or stickers at it, you may easy create a holo effect just by pressing it too tough or keeping it for too long in one spot, which will look bad in the sun, so better stick to manual job at the begging. 

Also, if you cannot hide in the garage (with proper forced ventilation) you may want to skip the paint job if it's a tree pollen season. Did some cleaning before applying wax on my car. Before I finished cleaning it was dirty already - this may ruin the paint job.", 'Chris you a  legend man']

['A common question in the comments is how can we have a junkyard engine and still be below the $500 limit and here is the answer: 
The goal of the 24hrs of Lemons is to try to level the playing field by having a bunch of junk cars race. This is the most affordable wheel to wheel racing in the world. Since our engine blew at our first  race and we are putting in an equally junky 140k mile junkyard M54 engine which is what came stock with our car, the replacement engine does not count towards the budget. The new seals we installed to stop the oil leaks ($60) and the chain tensioner we installed ($6) does count and the headers ($100) definitely count but we were at $340 after selling everything we could from the car… So now we are at our $500 budget. I need to see if I can sell the cats because those are $400 but something tells me that we can’t haha. 
With that said, safety stuff does not count towards the $500 budget. Otherwise it’s impossible to race because the fire suppression system alone cost more than $500 and the cage cost $3800. Parts to make the car faster or perform better do count, but not stuff to save the drivers life. 
Now the “backup engine” is a good opportunity for a collab with another automotive YouTuber who wanted to get involved and is trying to grow his channel. We aren’t using the backup engine unless ours blows up again which I can’t imagine will happen (knock on wood). So that engine won’t count towards the budget because it’s not in the car at the start of the race. If we end up having to swap it in at the track, it still won’t count because the time it takes to swap it in will make it so we are not competitive anymore. The next race we would have to remove it and put in another junk engine or take penalty laps. 
Lmk if you have any more questions about the $500 budget. Again, the main goal is to prevent people dumping money into a car and have an unfair advantage because they have a bunch of money.', 'I just searched up “project car” and started watching from when you first got this car, now it’s 6 AM and I wanna build an endurance race car 🏎️ ❤', 'What oil anyalysis company did you use and have you done a YouTube on how to go about doing that?', 'Based on the combustion chamber, your mixture was right on!', 'Great data and analysis Chris!', 'Was that head cracked too? ["You should always go to O'Reilly or AutoZone instead of advance. Advance has a lot of lazy people and it takes them forever to come out to your vehicle. O'Reilly tends to be the best. Napa is even a bit better if they have one in your area. Also, there are tests done on the expensive vs. Cheap batteries and the cheap ones actually out do the expensive ones in certain test. It's more or less just money down the drain. The warranty is nice if you will keep the vehicle and hold onto your receipt.", "If you can, get a voltage meter that you can see at all times while driving. You can find ones online that go in the cigarette lighter if you have a car old enough for that, and they also can have USB charging. You will be able to see what is going on with your electrical system during different times. You may be having under voltage at idle but fine at driving speeds, this would give you an issue if you're in stop and go traffic, the battery would never get charged back up. You may have good voltage at idle but overcharging at driving speeds, this could damage your battery and other electrical components with highway/interstate driving. You will also see what is going on after you've driven a while and the alternator has had a chance to heat up.

The alternator produces electricity based on the rpm of the engine, so if your engine is bogging down at idle, it will lower the amount of voltage and amperage the alternator produces. If your air conditioner is aging and long over due for service, it can bog down the drive belt by introducing mechanical resistance at idle, thus slowing down the alternator. You could also have have a misfire or other idling issue causing your rpm to drop below intended amounts after the engine has warmed up.


Alternators like being cold and dry. If it's a hot and humid day, your alternator is going to perform worse. They also will perform better at crank up and the true performance may not be detected for a while until it starts heating up. So I highly recommend getting a voltage and even an amperage meter in your vehicle so you know what's actually going on during different conditions.", 'My dad’s battery is dying right now so can you help me and my dad find a good battery? My cable had come adrift the other (UK passenger) side.  No need to remove the splashshield/front undertray but you cannot see the latch too well as there is a large pipe in the way.  Nevertheless there is plenty of room to get you hand round it and release the latch with your fingers - no pry bar required.  The cable was good except the nylon bush which keeps the actuator/bullet/nipple in place had perished.  Rather than replace the whole cable I am currently looking into what may provide a suitable replacement.  A nylon bush or electrical cable sleeve with a slit cut for the cable to be inserted into are the current favourites!  EDIT:  In the end the solution was to thread a 6mm spring washer around the cable to the left of the nipple as viewed fro the front of the car.  It was then possible to lassoo the washer using two 100mm cable ties and secure the latter to the latch arm.  One 100mm cable tie may suffice but would require much greater dexterity.  remember to squeeze the ends of the washer closed and pull the cable ties as tight as they will go!', "Any advice on the driver's side door not working. I've seen everything on the door not opening from the outside. My problem is that it won't open from the inside"]

['Good info.', 'Should I drain my transmission fluid twice or three more times.', 'So what the bell do we do if it’s black lol ?', "Good advise. Just a few additional comments, starting from the back: Yes, if your car wants Mercon V, then use only Mercon V, and that means specifically: ONLY real Mercon V, and NOT some multi vehicle ATF, which claims that is also fulfils Mercon V requirement, but most probably does not. And this is also very true for ZF Lifeguard 6, as used in some Jaguar S-Types: Do not use multi vehicle ATF, in investigated that meticulously. And as your video features the Jag X-Type: Kudos for pointing out correctly the fluid check bolt under the car, but checking the level is more complicated as you explained: Jag needs to be jacked up level, e.g. safely on stands, ATF temperature needs to be around 40° Celsius AND the ENGINE needs to be RUNNING when you remove the bolt to check the TF level on the X-Type. And back to ZF Lifeguard 6: That ATF has - when new - a light brownish colour. Hence, there your explanation about how to judge the age of the ATF based on its colour (red = good) does not apply, as this was never red. But yes: Black is bad. And the question change or flush would never cross my mind - I'd also do a flush, as I also would not do an engine oil change by dumping the old engine oil only to refill 50% of the old engine oil and adding just 50% of new engine oil. And many people think that a flush is not possible on the Jag X-Type, but it is. ["To the smart asses saying they just wouldn't be lazy and check their tire pressure with an analog gauge. If your that proactive about checking your pressure good for you. But what you arent proactive enough to do is check your wheel temp.  So when your temp is significantly higher on one wheel compared to the other three you'll know somethings wrong and have it checked out. Its how i was able to diagnose that my wheel bearing was bad even though it hadnt started to make a  clear sound yet. But it did save me from chewing up a $300+ tire too badly. I think it had just started to cup. But it could have been a bad caliper or a couple other things thats best to catch as early as possible. Ill always have a tpms monitor system on my vehicle and trailers. Its an invaluable tool. Anyone saying otherwise is woefully misinformed on exactly what they do. ["I tried all of these suggestions, with mixed and unsatisfying results.  My wife suggested Citrasolv (also spelled Citra solv) in concentrated form.  Waited for a warm/hot day when the sap was soft.  Put some Citrasolv on a shop rag and smeared a little on the actual spot, and after a couple of seconds started wiping until the sap was gone.  Doesn't take long, don't have to rub particularly hard, doesn't leave a halo or indication that sap was there at all.  I had sap all over my car so I was a wiping fool, and afterwards I ran it through a car wash.  Sap is gone, no damage to the car paint or clear coat.", 'I have cars that are ready in need of deep cleaning! ['🇵🇬🇵🇬,mm,', "I just want to make a short comment and yes it definitely is similar to a fuse or relay however there's nothing in today's world that replaces a fusible link unfortunately. Have a 1990 Dodge van that has a lot of fusible links I would love to substitute them but it is very complicated because even though they protect in the same manner there's nothing that will allow a current to come through and not pop it the way a fusible link works. A fuse any current coming through that is too high will pop at immediately relay will turn it off and then turn it back on immediately.. fusible link allows up to 3 seconds of current to go through so if you have surges in the system (an old van like mine there are many) The fusible link allows for them whereas the fuses and relays don't. Many people replace them but there are issues with doing that I wish there was a direct replacement. It's fine when you have one fusible link but when you have 20 of them it's really a pain", 'you said "don\'t forget to put the heat shrink on the wires before soldering and crimping"...what do you mean, because how can you crimp and solder if the plastic heat shrink is already over the area being fused?', 'Use flux next time and it will look as good as your example did', "I need you in my lifetime you're the reason I work and fix whatever I can but I also know when to leave it to the pros. Very thorough and don't listen to anyone else's opinions on how soldering looks. If it is bonded together WHO CARES? I THINK YOU DID AN AMAZING JOB", "Your soldering result was ugly because your soldering iron didn't produce sufficient heat for that job & because you didn't use sufficient flux.  Good vid nevertheless--it shows the essential info, so thank you!", 'The FL is usually tinned copper high stranding wire with a Hypalon (high temp, will not catch fire) insulating jacket. An blown FL will have a rippled and distorted look to the jacket (insulation). Although, as seen in the video, the failure mode is more often corrosion than an internally shorted Alternator.\n\nI prefer to use round barrel step down butt splices (hydraulic crimp) with Red dual wall heat shrink when repairing FLs. I do not solder fusible links. One of the many reasons is, for a large wire gauge splice like in the video, is the amount of heat needed to solder the joint correctly can actually over temp the FL jacket which will make it look like it experienced and overload (over temp) condition, because this is how you identify an overloaded FL. So, to avoid this, it is best to use a barrel butt splice connection(s).', 'Why would that link make your speedometer move??', 'Hey Boss, what kind of crimp is that? ['How do I fix the camber on my rear wheels? No shop can fix it, and both of my rear tires sit with an unexplained negative camber. ['Muy buenas. Como antiguo propietario de un Supra MK4 (biturbo, volante izquierda, targa, y manual), coincido prácticamente en todo lo que has comentado en el video. Sin embargo te diré que con la versión biturbo, se disfruta mas, lógicamente por llevar 100cv mas. Lo de la rigidez del chasis en la versión targa es totalmente cierto que notas como el coche se retuerce. El consumo real está por encima de 15/16 litros con una conducción mixta. Las plazas traseras, para que alguien normal quepa, las plazas delanteras hay que echarlas para adelante bastante. Provocando así una incomodidad a conductor y copiloto. Siendo honesto y por muy enamorado que siga estando de este coche, no es para tanto (desde mi humilde opinión). Y los precios reales a día de hoy, rondan los 40.000€ los mas baratos y hasta 150.000€ que alguno he visto. Por ese precio tienes coches nuevos que le meten al Supra una señora paliza. Este coche te tiene que entrar por los ojos y bolsillos para que te decantes por el. Si lo potencias, puedes tener un juguete muy picante, pero realmente no tan bueno como nos parece. Con no mucho dinero te pones en 500cv. Para superar los 1000cv ya tienes que añadir miles de euros mas. \nY para terminar con este comentario, me gustaría añadir que, aun opinando como he opinado, me encantaría volver a tener uno. ['Voy a explicar lo de las ruedas en lluvia que veo mucha gente comentandolo.

Con ruedas mas anchas es mas facil hacer aguaplaning, es decir cuando hay balsas de agua en la carretera el coche se desliza mas facil sobre ellas, como una tabla en la orilla de la playa. 

Pero en lluvia, con la carretera simplemente mojada, unas ruedas mas anchas deslizan menos lateralmente, frenan mejor y en resumen agarran mas.

Cuando es recomendable llevar finas es con nieve, con charcos, o cuando tu coche es muy ligero y no tiene nada de carga aerodinamica, como los utilitarios. En resumen cuando es mas util que "se hinque" en la superficie a que se agarre. 

Diferencias reales en un coche tipico (golf): 
- Con neumaticos de 195mm haces aguaplaning a 87,8kmh y con 225mm a 85kmh
- En mojado los anchos frenan antes y agarran bastante mas en curvas.

['Espero que os guste el coche, aclaro unos detalles en los que no me queria extender (+tocho)

No os quedeis con que los compresores son mejores que los turbos porque no tiene por que.
Lo digo porque estoy recibiendo mensajes de gente con coches turbo que quieren quitarlo y ponerle un compresor *(wtf)*

Si *es mejor en este caso* es porque no es un motor al que se le deba sacar mucha potencia si quieres cuidarlo, la transmision y los internals no aguantarian bien el par de un turbo, ni siquiera pasar de 350cv sin cambiar medio motor y la caja de cambios.

No es viable ni rentable ponerle algo asi a tu arosa o coches de ese tipo, lo mejor en casi todos los casos es directamente cambiar de coche a uno mejor. Si no lo hago en este es porque no hay muchos mas coches como este que no sean superdeportivos carisimos que no me puedo permitir (si, para mi este coche es un "quiero y no puedo" de un lexus lfa)

La gracia de este coche y uno de los motivos por los que me gusta es porque esta pensado para un tipo de uso y para transmitir unas *sensaciones, que directamente se perderian si le pongo un turbo.* Pero poniendo un compresor mantienes todo eso igual, aunque es dificil de explicar porque no es algo que se mida en cifras.

Cuando digo que bajar un coche, aumentarle el tamaño de las ruedas y hacerlo mas ancho no sirve para nada me refiero en la vida real en la calle, no en un circuito o en el gran turismo. 

Pero aun asi, incluso en circuito, un coche como este que apenas da 180cv reales de serie, con unas ruedas enormes lo unico que va a hacer es gastar mas gasolina, ser mas lento y mas torpe. 
Porque esas llantas aunque son la ostia de bonitas, pesan un huevo y son bastante mierder, mientras las de serie son super ligeras y top, al final es mucho mas util poner unos neumaticos buenos si quieres agarre. 

Y normalmente cuando compensa poner ruedas mas grandes es en coches con tanta potencia que no pueden transmitirla al suelo y salen quemando rueda durante 2 o 3 marchas (es lo que hice en el camaro porque son 435nm de par, el gt86 unos 200nm)

Y lo de los escapes que hacen ruido y tal pues bueno va en gustos, pero si no dejas dormir a la gente como seria mi caso pues te merecerias una pedrada y lo sabes jaja.
Si viviese lejos de la ciudad que es algo que me gustaria en un futuro pues entonces ni tan mal, aunque lo pondria con valvula y control remoto para cerrar el escape al llegar a zonas con gente como hizo ford con el nuevo mustang.

Casi siempre cuento estas cosas y luego al editar el video las acabo borrando, porque si llego a contar todo esto el video habria durado 20 minutos y seria un rollo.
Yo los hago para que sean entretenidos y pasarlo bien viendolos, asi que espero que los disfruteis y os sean utiles. Ah y vuestros coches tambien tal como estan (el tipico no hagais esto en casa jaja)', 'Que poco sabes', 'Ahora un litro de gasolina 98 cuesta como 2€ 💀', 'Pero y ese sonido feo?', 'Hola donde conseguiste la suspensión alguna que me recomiendas 😮 me topa en todas partes', 'Dónde encuentras los kits de kompressor para cada uno de tus coches? ['Creo que a algunas empresas o incluso gente con hibridos no les hara mucha gracia este video :P

La realidad es que lo mas ecologico y lo mejor en la mayoria de casos es *quedarte con tu antiguo coche* y repararlo mientras te sea rentable.

Pero tambien es igual de cierto que muchos hibridos aunque sean complejos y sigan contaminando son muy fiables, y si los usas sobretodo por ciudad pueden consumir mucho menos. No es lo ideal ya que eso seria "consumir 0" pero aun asi no estan mal.

Para mi los hibridos actuales se quedan a mitad de camino por los intereses que hay detras, y los electricos les llevan demasiada ventaja en comparacion, pero aun asi para mucha gente entre la que me incluyo, los electricos no son viables para su tipo de vida, su casa, o su pais.

Por eso, si compras un hibrido hazlo sabiendo lo que compras y no lo hagas solo por la legislacion, sobretodo si vives en un pais sin apenas seguridad juridica ya que en dos dias te cambian las leyes y te quedas con algo que ni te gusta, ni te sirve para entrar a ciudad.
 
PD: No me gusta hacer videos tecnicos ni muy serios pero me parecia util contarlo ;)', 'Hyundai ioniq Híbrido rueda 225/17 140cv = consumo medio global 4.4L.  En Ciudad por debajo de 4L. Lo demás son tecnologías en pañales. Fin.', 'Motos y bicis eléctricas. Te subes la batería de las primeras o directamente la bici a casa para recargar y movilidad absoluta en tu ciudad. Y el coche para viajar. Soy motero y con una scuter por muy cutre que sea, ya dominas tú la movilidad, y no te domina ella a ti. En Madrid se ven cuatro gatos en moto (en invierno dos) y en bici algún "loco" Pero en esta ciudad y en otras muchas de Spain tenemos una coche dependitis crónica. Ahora con motos y bicis eléctricas nadie se pasa a ellas... Nadie habla de ese modelo de movilidad (movilidad personal, claro, ya no hablo del transporte público!! Qué dices??!!) Incomprensible. Hasta los patinetes eléctricos se usan más. En China y en India to dios va en bici o en motillos o simplemente enganchados a los trenes como garrapatillas. ['Respondiendo las preguntas tipicas. 

* "Que es mejor, el patinete o la bici?" 
Depende de tus necesidades, son igual de buenos. 
- Quieres ir de pie, por ciudad, y meterlo plegado en sitios pequeños = patin 
- Quieres ir sentado, por el barro/piedras, y te da igual que ocupe algo mas = bici 

* "Te paga xiaomi? te regala los productos?" 
No, ni siquiera he hablado con ellos.
Si sabeis de otra marca fiable y barata que haga cosas asi poned enlaces que los miro.

* "Por que no subes un video de coches todas las semanas? o mas videos!" 
- Comprar un coche = 1000€ (minimo) / mantenerlo cada año 1000€ 
- Restaurarlo = Se tarda semanas o hasta meses, depende como este. 
Voy a mi ritmo y haciendo lo que me gusta. 

* "Para que tienes tantas bicis? o patinetes y cosas similares."
Si tienes 4 coches a ojo son 4000€ menos al año aunque no los uses. 
Una bici no cuesta "nada", la compras, la disfrutas, y luego la vendes casi por lo mismo. 

* "Me gustan las tomas falsas, pon mas" 
Eso solo depende de cuanto la cague, igual en un proximo video hablo del tema.', 'Buenas ! Tengo esta bicicleta pero no me van bien los frenos. Que tengo que comprar si sabes o que hago. 1.- Primero quita las burbujas soplando en el filamento, sino se te quedará la marca en la pieza que quieras imprimir. Las burbujas no aparecen si el filamento lo pones con cuidado sobre la superficie del agua la cual para mejorar la hidroimpresión debe de estar a unos 30°C.
2.- al quitar las burbujas llega el momento de echar el spray activador y tal y como aparece en tu vídeo no estás echando lo suficiente porque tiene que quedar pegajoso y semiliquido. Yo al echar el activador hago una prueba en la esquina del filamento para comprobar el estado del filamento al echarle el activador. Hay que dejar actuar el activador claro está y si sigue sin disolverse echar un poco más. Esto depende de la marca del activador. El mejor activador ya no se fabrica y es el HG arts.
3.- Sumerge la pieza despacio y en diagonal y cuando termines saca la pieza despacio. Después puedes darle con un chorro de agua para quitar la rebaja que se le queda.
4.- dejar secar y luego rociar una capa de laca transparente para mejorar el acabado y la resistencia.
